LX. ΟΝ “HYLUS‚’' A POPULAR HARANGUER.

ARGUMENT.

If you want to woo sweet sleep, seek not the silence of the night or the noise of water gliding by, or song of birds, or tones of the lyre, or the grains of poppy seed. You need not go to couch or take exercise or woo slumber through eating dainties or drinking wine. To compass sleep that knows no interruption, you have only to hear while Hylus harangues.

LX. DE HYLO CONCIONATORE.

Qui dormire paras, nocturna silentia noli Quaerere, nec strepitum praetereuntis aquae; Neo voluerum, nec quos edit lyra tinnula cantus, Quaeque soporiferum grana papaver habet ;

Nec molli te crede toro, nec membra fatiga, Nec dape, nec sumpto lumina conde mero:

Ut sopor obrepat non expugnabilis, audi, Dum coram populo rhetoricatur, Hylum.
